DEFAULTSORT:2018 LSU Tigers Football Team}}\n[[Category:2018 Southeastern Conference football season|LSU]]\n[[Category:LSU Tigers football seasons]]\n[[Category:2018 in sports in Louisiana|LSU Tigers f]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American college football season}}\n{{Infobox NCAA team season\n  |year= 2018\n  |team= LSU Tigers\n  |sport= football\n  |image= Louisiana State University (block logo).svg\n  |image_size= 125px\n  |conference= Southeastern Conference\n|conference_link= Southeastern Conference\n  |short_conf= SEC\n  |division= Western Division\n  |CoachRank = 7\n  |APRank = 6\n  |CFPRank = \n  |record = 10\u20133\n  |conf_record = 5\u20133\n  |head_coach= [[Ed Orgeron]]\n  |hc_year=2nd full year as HC; 3rd overall\n  | off_coach=[[Steve Ensminger]] \n  | oc_year = 1st full year as OC; 9th overall\n  |off_scheme= [[Pro-style offense|Pro-style]]/[[Spread offense|Spread]]\n  | def_coach= [[Dave Aranda]]\n  | dc_year = 3rd\n  |def_scheme= [[3-4 defense|3\u20134]]\n  |stadium= [[Tiger Stadium (LSU)|Tiger Stadium]] (Capacity: 102,321)\n  | champion = Fiesta Bowl champion \n  | bowl       = [[2019 Fiesta Bowl (January)|Fiesta Bowl]]\n  | bowl_result = W 40\u201332 vs. [[2018 UCF Knights football team|UCF]] \n}}\n{{2018 SEC football standings}}\nThe '''2018 LSU Tigers football team''' represented [[Louisiana State University]] during the [[2018 NCAA Division I FBS football season]]. The Tigers played their home games at [[Tiger Stadium (LSU)|Tiger Stadium]] in [[Baton Rouge, Louisiana]] and competed in the West Division of the [[Southeastern Conference]] (SEC). They were led by second-year head coach [[Ed Orgeron]].\n\nThe Tigers, coming off a 9\u20134 season in [[2017 LSU Tigers football team|Orgeron's first full season]], began the year ranked 25th in the preseason [[AP Poll]]. In the first game of the year, the team defeated No. 8 [[2018 Miami Hurricanes football team|Miami (FL)]] in the [[Advocare Classic]] played at [[AT&T Stadium]] in [[Arlington, Texas]]. LSU won its next four games, including on the road against then-No. 7 [[2018 Auburn Tigers football team|Auburn]], and rose to fifth in the AP Poll, before falling on the road to [[2018 Florida Gators football team|Florida]]. The team rebounded with wins over No. 2 [[2018 Georgia Bulldogs football team|Georgia]] and No. 22 [[2018 Mississippi State Bulldogs football team|Mississippi State]] before being shutout by eventual SEC champions [[2018 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|Alabama]]. In the last game of the regular season, LSU lost on the road against [[2018 Texas A&M Aggies football team|Texas A&M]] in an FBS record-tying [[2018 LSU vs. Texas A&M football game|seven overtimes]]. The final score of the game, 74\u201372, set the FBS record for combined points in a single game (146). The team finished the regular season tied for second in the SEC's West Division and was invited to the [[2019 Fiesta Bowl (January)|Fiesta Bowl]] to play [[2018 UCF Knights football team|UCF]], which the Tigers won by a score of 40\u201332 to end UCF's active win streak of 25 games. LSU finished the season with an overall record of 10\u20133 and was ranked 6th in the final AP Poll.\n\nThe team's defense featured three [[2018 College Football All-America Team|consensus All-Americans]] in defensive backs [[Grant Delpit]] and [[Greedy Williams]], and linebacker [[Devin White]], who was awarded the [[Dick Butkus Award]] as the nation's best linebacker. On offense, the Tigers were led by redshirt junior quarterback [[Joe Burrow]], who finished with 2,894 passing yards and 23 total touchdowns (16 passing and 7 rushing). Senior running back Nick Brossette led the team in rushing with 1,039 yards and 14 touchdowns.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/schools/louisiana-state/2018.html|title=2018 LSU Tigers Stats|website=Sports-Reference.com|access-date=June 5, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Previous season==\nThe Tigers finished the [[2017 LSU Tigers football team|2017 season]] 9\u20134, 6\u20132 in SEC play to finish in third place in the Western Division. They were invited to the [[2018 Citrus Bowl|Citrus Bowl]] where they lost to [[2017 Notre Dame Fighting Irish football team|Notre Dame]].\n\n==Recruiting==\n\n===Position key===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n|[[Running back|Back]]\n|'''B'''\n|rowSpan=\"6\" style=\"background-color:lightgrey;\"|\n|[[Center (American football)|Center]]\n|'''C'''\n|rowSpan=\"6\" style=\"background-color:lightgrey;\"|\n|[[Cornerback]]\n|'''CB'''\n|rowSpan=\"6\" style=\"background-color:lightgrey;\"|\n|[[Defensive back]]\n|'''DB'''\n|-\n|[[Defensive end]]\n|'''DE'''\n|[[Defensive lineman]]\n|'''DL'''\n|[[Defensive tackle]]\n|'''DT'''\n|[[End (American football)|End]]\n|'''E'''\n|-\n|[[Fullback (American football)|Fullback]]\n|'''FB'''\n|[[Guard (American football)|Guard]]\n|'''G'''\n|[[Halfback (American football)|Halfback]]\n|'''HB'''\n|[[Placekicker|Kicker]]\n|'''K'''\n|-\n|[[Kickoff returner]]\n|'''KR'''\n|[[Offensive tackle]]\n|'''OT'''\n|[[Lineman (American football)|Offensive lineman]]\n|'''OL'''\n|[[Linebacker]]\n|'''LB'''\n|-\n|[[Long snapper]]\n|'''LS'''\n|[[Punter (American football)|Punter]]\n|'''P'''\n|[[Punt returner]]\n|'''PR'''\n|[[Quarterback]]\n|'''QB'''\n|-\n|[[Running back]]\n|'''RB'''\n|[[Safety (American and Canadian football position)|Safety]]\n|'''S'''\n|[[Tight end]]\n|'''TE'''\n|[[Wide receiver]]\n|'''WR'''\n|}\n\n===Recruits===\n\nThe Tigers signed a total of 22 recruits.\n\n{{College Athlete Recruit Start|40=no|collapse=yes|year=2018}}\n{{College Athlete Recruit Entry\n| recruit  = Damone Clark\n| position = LB\n| hometown = [[Baton Rouge, LA]]\n| highschool = Southern University Laboratory School\n| feet   = 6\n| inches = 3\n| weight = 218\n| commitdate = January 15, 2017\n| scout stars  = 4\n| rivals stars = 4\n| 247 stars = 4\n| espn stars = 3\n}}\n{{College Athlete Recruit Entry\n| recruit  = Travez Moore\n| position = DE\n| hometown = [[Bastrop, LA]]\n| highschool = [[Copiah\